          "title": "Acts 3 in Luke's narrative architecture",
          "body": "Acts 3 is not a freestanding miracle story; it is engineered to set up Acts 4-5. The sign provokes the sermon; the sermon draws the crowd; the crowd provokes the arrest (4:1-3); the arrest produces the first apostolic defense before the Sanhedrin (4:5-22); the defense produces the prayer of the church and the second filling of the Spirit (4:23-31). Without Acts 3, Acts 4 has no occasion. Luke is also paralleling Peter's ministry to Jesus' own: where Jesus healed paralytics and preached at the temple, Peter now does the same in Jesus' name. The apostle is not the agent; he is the witness — and the chapter shows that to be a witness is to deflect every glance from yourself to the risen Christ."
